---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Our Home Coffee Cost Methodology | The Brewdown"
  description="How The Brewdown estimates home brewing costs: machine upfront, daily ingredients, and per-method cafe spending over a multi-year comparison."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-[var(--gutter)] py-10 md:py-14">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-3">About · The Brewdown</p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 font-display text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink md:text-5xl">
      Straight talk on what home coffee actually costs
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-ink-2">
      The Brewdown helps cost-conscious households compare the total cost of brewing at home across
      pods, bean-to-cup, bulk brew, and manual espresso. No jargon, no hobbyist rabbit holes: just
      numbers you can adjust to match your habits.
    </p>

    <section class="mt-10 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">How estimates work</h2>
      <p class="text-ink-2">
        Each comparison line adds three parts: an upfront machine cost on day one, ongoing home
        brewing (ingredients at your cups-per-day rate), and that method's expected coffee shop
        spending. We do not spread machine cost across years; a $800 bean-to-cup machine shows up as
        $800 at the start of the chart, not amortized over time.
      </p>
      <p class="text-ink-2">
        The cumulative cost chart spans 60 months internally. That horizon is a modeling choice for
        the calculator, not a promise about how long your gear will last. Results update live as you
        change inputs; everything runs in your browser with no account and no data sent to our
        servers.
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-ink-2">
        <li>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Included:</strong> machine upfront cost, home
          ingredients (beans, grounds, or pods), and per-method café visits at your shop drink price.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Excluded:</strong> electricity, water, milk,
          syrups, tips, labor, and the time you spend brewing.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-10 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">Fewer café visits matter</h2>
      <p class="text-ink-2">
        Better home setups often mean fewer trips to the coffee shop. Each method carries its own
        default shop drink frequency: bean-to-cup assumes fewer residual café visits than pods, for
        example. That difference shows up in the breakdown and can steepen long-term savings beyond
        cheaper per-cup home brewing alone.
      </p>
      <p class="text-ink-2">
        Defaults are starting points based on typical habits, not predictions about your life. Adjust
        coffee shop drinks per method to reflect how you actually buy coffee away from home.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-10 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">Default dollar amounts</h2>
      <p class="text-ink-2">
        Example machine and ingredient prices come from publicly listed retail ranges and
        illustrative research. They are meant for comparison, not as quotes for a specific product. Example
        drinks are based on the classic 6oz cup. Espresso machine samples are based on cappuccino at the 
        midpoint of a popular 18g double and classic 9g single shot. Override any field with prices from 
        your cart, local shops, or recent purchases.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-10 rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 px-5 py-5 shadow-md">
      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-ink">Illustrative only</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-ink-2">
        The Brewdown provides illustrative cost estimates only. It is not financial, tax, or
        investment advice. Actual costs depend on the products you buy, how often you brew, and local
        prices. Use the calculator to explore scenarios, not as a sole basis for purchasing
        decisions.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
